The Ekiti State government said it is considering stiffer sanctions against people still engaging in indiscriminate dumping of refuse and perpetrators of all forms of environmental sanitation offences in Ekiti state. The Commissioner for Information, Mr. Muyiwa Olumilua who disclosed this to journalists said plans were in the pipeline by the state government to tighten noose through stricter legislation that stipulates high punishment for such offenders. The collaborating groups, during the programme, embarked on street cleaning in Ado Ekiti metropolis, particularly at the popular Oja Oba Market and other strategic areas within the town. According to Olumilua, who spoke alongside his Ministry of Environment counterpart, Gbenga Agbeyo, the measure will help to promote the culture of cleanliness and curtail outbreak of infectious diseases in Ekiti. “The outbreak of coronavirus and Lassa Fever diseases was enough to convince us that we have to promote cleanliness in our dear state. We must stop blocking waterways to check flooding, indiscriminate dumping of refuse and felling of trees, they cause hazards of monumental proportion”, he warned. Agbeyo revealed that the government has sought amendment at the assembly to the existing environmental law that would specify more stringent punishment for violators of environmental sanitation laws when passed and assented to. The Chief Executive Officer of the Triple G Eco Revival Solutions, Oluwaseyi Ebenezer, lamented how the people are taking the issue of hygienic environment for granted due to ignorance. “It is sad that people are still doing open dumping of their household refuse even in the state capital. This method of waste disposal does not only litter our streets, but causes blockage of some water channels making our state prone to flooding,’’ he said. 